[6] Guadeloupe
Date: Wed 12 May 2010]
Source: Google News Francais [in French, trans. Corr.SB, edited]
<http://guadeloupe.rfo.fr/infos/actualites/dengue-epidemie-confirmee_23273.html>


The last report from the Epidemiological Institute of Health is
rather alarming. Since the beginning of April [2010], the number of
people affected by dengue continues to grow. For that, experts refer
to the number of people received in consultation and who have
symptoms of dengue, namely a high fever, headache, muscle aches and
joint pain, rash, or vomiting. This number is 500 per week, a rate 7
times the maximum level observed during this same period [in 2009].

After analysis, the epidemic phase is confirmed and the case numbers
are stable. They vary between 40 and 60 per week. A peak at 80 was
observed in mid-March 2010 but dropped in the following weeks. The
number of people hospitalized from the disease is also stable. Of the
94 hospitalizations since the epidemic began, 16 were severe, and 24
have developed the DHF form of the disease.

Grande-Terre is the area most affected, especially the town of St.
Francis. The town itself is responsible for 10 percent of all cases
each month. Basse-Terre, Petit-Bourg and Sainte-Rose have the largest
number of cases since the beginning of the epidemic.

A combination of factors is behind the increase in cases. Heat, rain,
resistance of the mosquito, _Aedes aegypti_, to insecticides, and
many stagnant water places for mosquito breeding; these factors all
contribute to the disease [virus] spread.

The emphasis is on prevention. The goal is not to be breeding _Aedes
aegypti_, the mosquito vector of dengue [virus]. A communication plan
has been adapted and is in place. Insecticide spraying is ongoing as
are the checking operations on sites deemed to be sensitive.

The French Departments of the Americas are not equal on the dengue
front. Guadeloupe and Guyana are in phase 4 of program monitoring,
warning and management of epidemics, corresponding to a confirmed
outbreak. Martinique is one notch below. There, the epidemic is at
the risk stage.

[Byline: Karine Sigaud-Zebulun]

--
