[7] Guatemala
Date: Sun 16 May 2010
Source: Prensa Latina [in Spanish, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.plenglish.com//index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=188706&Itemid=5>


Today [16 May 2010], health authorities increase their work to combat
dengue in Escuintla department [state or province equivalent] in the
south of Guatemala. Above all, they are trying to avoid storage of
potable water, without the necessary precautions, that favor the
[breeding] of the agent that transmits the disease [virus], the
_Aedes aegypti_ mosquito.

Priority work is in the 4 municipalities where water is most scarce
and [where] coincidentally 261 of the 313 [dengue] registered
infected individuals are concentrated. A "yellow alert" was declared
in this department since, in the course of this year [2010], the
number of [dengue] cases is greater than in all of 2009, when there
were 307 [cases], 208 with classical dengue and 99 of DHF. For this
last variety [type of disease - DHF], 90 infected individuals have
been counted, of which a girl died this past March [2010].

[There is] a campaign together with information developed by various
municipal government institutions in which the specialists try to
identify the so-called "red zones" where the greatest proliferation
of the vector mosquito exists.

However, this work faces difficulties due to the negative [reaction]
of some residents stopping investigation of the interior of their
dwellings [to check on] the possibility of vector breeding sites.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT
<promed-port@promedmail.org>

