[8] Nicaragua
Date: Thu 13 May 2010
Source: El Nuevo Diario [in Spanish, trans & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.elnuevodiario.com.ni/nacionales/74361>


The rainy season still has not reached its apogee, and in the country
there have been increased numbers of affected individuals registered
due to diseases related to this season. Just in the capital
[Managua], 2784 dengue cases have been recorded. Most of the affected
individuals are children 3-5 years of age.

In the most recent weeks, there has been an upsurge of dengue in
Guatemala, El Salvador and Costa Rica.

There have been several deaths from the disease. Nicaragua still has
sequelae from last year's [2009] outbreak. Officials from the
Ministry of Health (MINSA) state that, currently, there is [dengue]
virus circulation, and while this situation goes on, the populace
does not comply with hygiene and sanitary measures at home, so we
will continue to be affected by dengue.

"We, as the responsible ministry, have not lowered our guard since
the beginning of the dengue outbreak. However, currently in Managua,
we have 2784 suspected dengue cases, of which 378 are positive. These
are distributed all over the capital, in both rural and urban areas,"
said the person responsible for the vector transmission program of
MINSA, Maria Dolores Flores. Since this past April [2010], the Local
Integrated Health System, Silas-Managua, initiated an abate [_Aedes_
larvicide] effort and recently began fumigation; however, despite
that both activities are free, the people do not permit the personnel
of the [health] brigades to enter their houses. Because of this, "we
must remind the populace that all MINSA personnel carry
identification, and their vehicles are labeled. Moreover, we travel
in groups of 20 or more people," Flores insisted.

However, the main problem which the health workers have found is the
excess of trash which is in the streets, ditches and in the houses.
All of this discarded [trash] accumulation, with the rains, makes for
mosquito breeding sites. She also stated that, "the people must be
clear that dengue kills, without respect to color, race, social
status or political creed. Although, for now, nobody has died due to
this disease, we have had very serious cases in intensive care units.
Last year [2009], there were 9126 cases in this outbreak," she also said.

[Byline: Jasmina Escobar Sandino]

--
