[9] Ecuador (Galapagos): Request for Information (RFI)
Date: Wed 12 May 2010
From: Name withheld on request [edited]


I have been on the island of San Cristobal, Galapagos for the past 2
weeks. I am a public health doctor, and, interestingly, given the
situation I am about to describe, my friend here with me works in
tropical medicine.

Since we have arrived, there have been widespread reports of dengue,
both on this island and the other main island, Santa Cruz. Here in
Cristobal, it is widely discussed and accepted that much of the
population has already experienced, or is coming down now, with
dengue like symptoms, i.e. fever, headache, myalgias, lethargy and
some reports of arthralgia and rash (non petechial) associated with
the resolution of the fever. Indeed, among my extended family here,
there are currently only 2 or 3 who have not experienced symptoms out
of over 30. Word of mouth has it that there have been at least 500
hospital presentations and many more who are staying at home.

My own symptoms began 2 days ago, with myalgias and fatigue and a
fever at night. My 3-year-old daughter has also had a fever since
yesterday, and most of the family have experienced symptoms in the
preceding month or so, although many are still coming down with
symptoms now. A sister-in-law and her husband were bed-bound, and we
had to put drips up in their house because the single hospital on the
island is full, all with dengue, we are told.

Since arriving there, have been many Ministry of Public Health
officials here fogging with malathion (we are told) and putting some
kind of granular insecticide [probably abate, a larvicide - Mod.TY]
in the stored water tanks that are very common in the houses here.
There have been reports on the local television news as well as local
radio about the dengue outbreak.

Before leaving to come to Galapagos, we were aware of reports from
mid March [2010] of isolated dengue cases in San Cristobal; however,
there does not appear to be a single further mention of the situation
anywhere that we can find on ProMED or any of the other sites we have
looked at, such as CDC and WHO, or even on the Ministry of Public
Health of Ecuador site, as far as we can tell.

I cannot understand why there have been no further reports on ProMED
since mid-March 2010. Is this because cases are not confirmed
serologically? Is it because there are no formal reports? Is there
some other reason that is known? I would have thought that given
there is some kind of outbreak going on here, with a very high attack
rate from all concerned, that something should have filtered onto ProMED.

Do you have any information at all, such as the strain, the epidemic
curve, islands affected, total number of cases including any dengue
haemorrhagic fever?

--
Communicated by:
A physician, name withheld on request

[The physician who submitted this report raises critical questions
about the lack of information on what appears to be a significant
dengue outbreak on 2 of the Galapagos Islands. ProMED requests
information about this situation. It is very difficult to avoid
reporting of dengue outbreaks in important tourist destinations, and
failure to do so has the potential for damaging the credibility of
the responsible public health agencies.

[A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Ecuador showing the
location of the Galapagos Islands can be accessed at
<http://healthmap.org/promed/en?v=-1.4,-78.8,5>. - Mod.TY]

